According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid of Nevada, the legislators are therefore seeking a permanent settlement in Congress on Sunday.
This is to reassure investors before trading on the Asian financial markets, where, due to the time zone, Congress's decision could be the first to influence Monday's trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two chambers of the US Congress are voting on the law, and neither is it possible that the trial cannot be blocked at the last minute because of any problem.
The legislators hope that the law will be approved in the following days.
However, the law is still undergoing a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the scheme shall be divided into two parts.
At the request of President George Bush, the first $350 billion should be available as soon as possible.
However, the Congress may block the issue of the remaining amount, which was set at an additional $100 billion and later $350 billion if it feels that the programme does not fulfil its function.
Bush evaluated progress in the negotiations
