According to Marek, it's not so important that the plan is approved now or at the beginning of next week.
"It is much more important that Congress decide this week to support the plan and give their blessing as soon as possible.
The spiritual importance of agreeing that the plan will be approved is the most important thing at this moment," stressed Marek.
A few fights on the edge: MP3 players versus cell phones.
Helping to Choose
While almost all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
It makes sense that it's better to just buy phones.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons why you should get a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the needs of the prospective owner.
It's probably hard to get a high-end record player at home to listen to the newest Maxim Turbulenc record.
On the one hand, such music products do not appear on vinyl plates, but there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
However, if his shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues vinyl records, he probably dreams of such a record player.
This is similar to that intended for travel, i.e. compressed - simplified with MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories here.
For some it may be unacceptable to rent 8,000 crowns for a player, as a Pink Floyd fan may find it difficult to accept a market headphone with 20 crowns.
There are two extremes between which everyone has enough space.
There's a wide selection.
The life of the elements also counts
Some high-end music players can do much more than simply play music, but also what most mobiles do not happen to do.
No current device is as universal as a phone.
In addition to the primary features, phone calls and text messages, you can play music and videos, record both, have a right-worst camera, and even navigate.
And if you consider the smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no fridge can barbecue and no television can take pictures.
Multiple-function cell phones have drawbacks.
The more features you use on your mobile, the more the display sends you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
That's why with cheap cell phones, count on them not to play for you for more than a few hours.
If you even make a phone call here and there, get a charger for your workplace just in case - this also applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players will not have such problems, even worse ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one upload.
The next problem arises when the music is uploaded to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices have a universal USB connector and not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers can cope without adapters with miniature memory cards used in mobile phones.
With a few exceptions (iPod) players do not need any special software.
It's enough to fill the device from the computer with music through USB.
The majority of mobiles and players are already creating a musical library in order based on the name of the performer, the album, the genre, or for example the user's evaluation.
Some devices represent only tree structures like Windows Explorer, and know some of them both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to handle, mobiles know more
When selecting the specific equipment, please check the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of the treatment.
If music serves as a background for you and only listens to it for a short time a day, for example on the tram, any mobile that plays MP3 will suit you.
And any cell phone can do that now.
You don't even have to pay particular attention to the music formats that the mobile or player can use.
MP3 can handle all of them and the vast majority of the music you receive will be in this format.
MP3 is one of the most common and the vast majority of devices can also cope with WMA format music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPod) is less common.
Better mobiles also allow, for example, online music shopping.
It is enough to visit the appropriate pages of the service provider (or other service provider) via the mobile internet and to buy the song or album.
This service can in itself be a strong argument for the purchase of a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of service providers is lousy and usually limited to one-year radio hits.
Prices aren't the lowest either.
However, it is generally assumed that such a way of selling music (either via GSM, Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people keep their cell phones with them all the time.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you feel your cell phone in your pocket while the forgotten MP3 player is at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your headphones or at least your speakerphones.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost all mobile players have, but only a few MP3 players.
For many, the biggest advantage of music mobiles is the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kroner.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get a decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you are limited by the lack of traditional earphone output.
The best and most technically equipped phones can cost up to fifteen thousand kroner with traditional 3.5 mm diameter headphones.
However, the advantage of players is, among other things, simple handling.
The simplest - by no means necessarily the cheapest players (see our selection) can really be handled by everyone.
Minimal function, the treatment similar to the previous standard cassette tape recorder or gramophone is obvious.
There is no risk of collapse in the form of an accidentally switched-on mobile internet or in the case of a huge bill for the subsequent transmission of data.
What device to choose
The cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an opening to replace memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
Buying the right card will fit up to 2,000 kroner.
But be careful.
The basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive can do with up to 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and even want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Based on capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If it belongs to more demanding students, choose special mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, so the comfort of the treatment approaches the MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson was the biggest player in the sector, which has the same user interface as the individual MP3 players sold.
MP3 players in the above mentioned brands can offer the same service in the same price category up to four thousand kroner, but with higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The Czech mobile market is relatively developed and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, we are missing something here - a virtual provider that forces classic service providers to reduce their prices substantially.
Maybe it won't be for long.
On the Mobil.cz website we have often said that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by ČTÚ, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than that of other EU countries.
Following the recent action of the European Commission, the regulation of roaming charges may result in a conflicting situation - some of the Czech mobile operators' customers' text messages from abroad will be cheaper than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory, since we have three mobile networks and our penetration is high above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, has often agreed on this, who has said a few times that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classic service provider with its own network is no longer likely to have too much of a chance (though it would probably be difficult to find a frequency).
But there is one other option - the virtual service provider.
Just as virtual service providers entered the mobile market, significant price reductions were made, and then classic service providers had to respond to them.
In the meantime, even before big fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile were on the market in Britain, voices like ours were heard.
However, it has been proven that such providers have a place and can indeed be successful.
However, for example, we do not have to go too far.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the mobile virtual service provider in Poland.
This service provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers in less than six months and become the fifth largest service provider there.
In the meantime, Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic is also owned by U:fon.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility of focusing on a much narrower target group.
In order to be efficient, it needs much less customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not entail relatively high costs for building, mobile network operation and maintenance.
Virtual service providers generally appear in the world at low cost - offering cheap calls and text messages, which are often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers at least 50 percent cheaper text messages than its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobile in Poland shows, it is a pretty good move to bet on a target group.
This service provider focuses specifically on men.
"The real men choose the Mobilking service provider - who they like, whom they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of this virtual service provider Mobil Entertainment Company.
It is difficult to say whether the idea like that in Poland can work for us.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone spokesperson, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small to the segment approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfied with regard to the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, there is no chance, mobile operators claim
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not seem very hopeful.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our region," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta Financial Group in his telephone interview to Mobil.cz.
This indirectly demonstrated that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not very sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do their best to ensure that no potential competition can be created.
For some time, the GTS Novera Group has not been hiding its interest in the launch of the virtual service provider, which aims to take another step to make Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested to be able to provide not only landline but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner the better.
This option has been renegotiated with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl, spokesperson for the group.
Maybe now's a better time.
From informal information, it seems that the first virtual service provider will be lucky by the end of the year.
His birth, however, is now surrounded by an impenetrable silence.
"At this moment, we do not think that a full-fledged virtual service provider should have a place on the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
So far, we have not been approached by a single subject, which offers a complex and serious project in this area," he mentioned to Mobil.cz about the press department of Telefónica 02, Vlastimil Sršeň.
The specific situation of the Czech market is also referred to by the other operators.
Martina Kemrová, spokesperson for T-Mobile, adds, exceptionally in agreement with O2, that "Until now we have not recorded any viable and bilaterally beneficial business projects on which to base further."
And he added: "In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will show up.
At this moment, we should have a specific agreement on our table so that we can think in such a short term."
Vodafone prefers to pay attention to its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
That's what we consider the most rewarding from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find partners to build networks shared with fast mobile internet."
Responsible offices - in a string with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of a new operator would mean an increase in competition, leading to a fall in prices and thus to a decrease in profits.
So why make it easy for such a competition to enter?
When service providers have something important, they are able to cooperate, they also testify to the long haul around the birth of U:fon.
The highest pressure on ČTÚ was probably around the birth of the U:phone of the T-Mobile company.
This is demonstrated by publicly available information on ČTÚ's website.
But right now, U:fon is a good reason why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: "The environment of competition in the mobile market has recently been eroded by the market access of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that another player's entry into the market and services would be subject to high requirements."
However, given this attitude of mobile operators, the total lack of interest of Czech regulators is absolutely astonishing.
Meanwhile, it is not just ČTÚ's attitude, which in the Czech Republic, unfortunately, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, has no right to intervene in economic competition.
Only the Hungarian Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
But the office has a distinctive attitude to the whole problem.
"The virtual service provider's entry into the mobile market would only be possible after a contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider is concluded on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the supply of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers," he said in response to our question about Kristian Chlapua, the External Relations Department of the Hungarian Competition Authority.
A statement from representatives of service providers thus formulated would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the office which should represent the interests of consumers and, above all, ensure that no one can abuse their market situation, this is more than odd.
Especially if Kristian Chalupa adds: "Outland, where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the price of mobile phone services."
However, the interests of the ÚOHS are probably not to put pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the price reduction.
In this case, it is indeed shocking to find a quite touching consistency from the reaction of the three mobile operators.
The question is whether it's really a coincidence, it's almost self-evident.
Just as the petrol prices at the filling stations are certainly just the work of chance and tough competition.
"The Office has not discovered any evidence of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers has a leading position, i.e. a correspondingly higher responsibility for their market activities.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual service providers are probably also missing the telecom regulator," said Chalupa.
The presentation of the market leader position is one of the many points of dispute.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ on the basis of which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, no Czech service provider is in a leading position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different approach - the virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator, relatively logically speaking, has a monopoly on its own network.
So, in a particular segment, it is necessarily dominant.
But even if this argument were not accepted, it should be a minimum warning for UOHS that three mobile operators act in the same way.
In the meantime, complaints from interested parties (including the already mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in the course of negotiations with all service providers.
Placing responsibility on ČTÚ is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which the UOHS takes its hand off the whole case.
We've seen this before in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, the expansion of ČTÚ's powers in the field of economic competition could not be carried through telecommunications, although many experts hoped to improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS need to know that, but their interests are probably different.
This works when no one's watching.
In the meantime, the operation of some kind of false virtual service provider remains undetected, many of which are already operational in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that issue their own mobile phone service price lists, but they are only partially public.
They are multilevel marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic company client against the service provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a top client, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial terms of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-emptions.
"If there were cases that he was talking about, the terms of the contract could be an infringement that we would be dealing with and which could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with the company in question," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
But it is highly unlikely that the news of this type of activity has not reached the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, thousands of customers may be involved in the three companies mentioned.
In the meantime, no service provider defends itself against such a procedure.
These companies have not had negligible profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual service providers, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card is not in their name on their phones, so they cannot have this in full as general customers of mobile operators."
But that's what ČTÚ should be strange about.
In addition, there is another question for the UOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to similar procedures, why do they prevent the birth of the virtual service provider?
It should be added that the UOHS has a relatively strong power to expose such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they did not suspect any such thing and that their commercial terms prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has already been said a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable decrease in the price of services.
In the meantime, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers are established, classic service providers have tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were virtually the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, in developed countries, regulatory bodies intervened at precisely these moments, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators but of their customers.
Then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider that others had followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are handing the whole thing to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competences are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may be back on the move.
If a service provider would allow the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, it would be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will no longer make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech state anthem.
On Sunday Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on Czech State Day presented the new recordings of the State Anthem Where Is My Country?
The anthem was recorded by the National Theatre orchestra led by Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo, choir or instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka sing.
The anthem was modified by the authors of Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on iHNed.cz.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had already told Czech Radio that he deliberately selected young representative singers who were expressive and popular for singing solo variations.
"From the beginning, I have tried to ensure a clear diction, a clear understanding of the text and consistency at both and later in the orchestra," he said.
The Czech state anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where Is My Country? was first performed in the Order Theatre in 1834 in Josef Kajtan's Tyl Fidlovačka, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously viewed it as their own.
The first verse of the song became a natural part of the state anthem after the formation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
After the formation of the independent Czech Republic, it remained one of the seven state symbols.
How's the "new" anthem?
The transport company in Prague will deliver with a chip card for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 enters the history of the Transport Company in Prague as the first passenger to enter metros, trams and buses to have an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper line ticket.
The coupon is currently available to about 100,000 people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase 30 days and 90 days and annual coupons (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time save them to their chip cards at the Metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraži Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday, coupons can be purchased via the Internet via the Transport Company www.dpp.cz website.
The service was used by more than 400 customers until the afternoon.
Those who start using Internet commerce can permanently forget about the subway stations' publishing windows, where they have had to regularly stand up long lines for the bar tickets.
The coupon can be purchased via the Internet and the Opencard card will be saved in one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
"In these places, passengers have at their disposal a counter with trained servers who help interested people buy online and save their purchased coupons for their cards," said Martin Opatrný, the project spokesperson.
In addition to the libraries, electronic coupons can be saved for Opencard in the self-service vending machines installed in some lobbys.
What do these vending machines look like?
They are red, reminding me of ticket managers, and the passengers may already have noticed them at the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in town, but they should be 80 by the end of the year," added Opatrný.
The coupon is automatically checked instead of the driver
The operation of the machines starting tomorrow is simple.
Just insert the Opencard chip card and a previously paid coupon will be saved by itself.
From tomorrow, electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital but also in the area.
So on the trains and bus lines around the city from 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants of the Central Czech districts travel to the capital.
"On trains classified in Prague's integrated transport, the guides were provided with card readers to identify the area validity of the coupons," explained Filip Drápal from the Ropid organization, which established the timetable for public transport in Prague.
In the busses around the city, card readers are installed at the cashier's office.
When boarding, the driver must not only show the chip card, but also place Opencard on the cashier's side.
That's how the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"For example, if the passenger needs to check the validity of coupons, it is the easiest way to ask the driver to do so," he added Dráp.
Passengers who do not drive buses around the city and will not remember when their coupon expires may again go to self-service vending machines that save coupons on cards.
Information on the validity of their documents is displayed here on the display of the equipment.
Sudetas wanted a referendum from the U.S.
In 1945, the Sudeta Germans asked for the addition of Šumava to the United States.
This comes from the letter in the collection of the Southern Czech Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the cartridge of the United States of America.
It was said that some groups of Sudeta Germans turned to the President of the United States in 1945 with this wish.
This can also be seen from a private archive that is preserved today in the collection of the Southern Czech Science Library.
In the letter from Česky Krumlov, the Germans asked the President of the United States not to allow the "šumava County" to be returned to the Czech Republic, which was occupied by Hitler under the Munich Treaty.
"The situation has been correctly understood and we really want to be sure of the words that American troops are in no way coming to the German territories as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," there is in the letter, signed with the words "People who care about Šumava's fate."
Since the addition to Czechoslovakia to the Sudeta Germans is supposed to give only hope of brutality, mercilessness, not understanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the US President to take over the Protectorate "now and forever" over Šumava.
