Rats have feelings, too.
A rat or a moth is on the run.
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals also have emotions.
But how can we examine whether they feel the same way when they act like us?
For years, famous scientists have been publishing their articles in the "Edge" Internet magazine.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in one of its series is looking at the answers to the question "What do you think is real without proving it?"
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as we examine other species and dissect questions of perception or consciousness in general, we come to difficult terrain, because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals, pretending to be dead, fleeing or attacking.
People behave in a similar way, suggesting that some researchers have comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to animals.
On the one hand, human consciousness-related circuits almost always contain the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and implementation/management functions).
This broad area is more advanced in humans than in other primates, and it seems that other organisms are completely absent.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, for example, the consciousness of who we are, or in the case of planning and decision-making ability, it is reasonable to assume that man is different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, the animals may be excluded.
However, even if the language was not dependent on the language, the language would certainly affect it, so the animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine what consciousness might be in the case of other animals.
If the mind cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and because of the special hardware, it cannot be analyzed based on our own experience, then its research will cause us serious problems.
Most of my discussions relate to the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness, which is probably more accessible to science.
The animal's conscious processes could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in the case of experiments on the short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
However, in this assumption also examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on the neural contexts of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both can be the same, whether or not.
Interestingly, this hypothesis also highlights the importance of prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualization.
What follows from this emotion?
I point out that an emotional system, like fear, is activated in a brain that is aware of its own activities.
What we call "fear" is, therefore, the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defence system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies a work memory.
Thus, emotions are closely linked to those areas of the cortex that are characteristic of primates and especially humans.
In addition to language, perception is divided into subtle degrees, because with the help of words and grammar, we are able to distinguish and categorize states so that we can describe them to others.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio is of the opinion that emotions come from simpler activities in the areas of the brain cortex and brain stem body perception, as well as Jaak Pankseep, who is more focused on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed very much in human evolution, it can easily play a role in species-wide emotions.
In theory, I can't deny that, but I find it unproveable.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to feel in both cases: How can it be checked whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave alike?
A cockroach flees in the event of danger, does he feel fear?
In my opinion, only similar behavior is not yet proof of the same experience.
Although neural comparison further helps: rats and humans have similar brain stem, cockroaches do not have brains.
But the brain stem is responsible for the emotions?
And even if it could be proved for humans, how can we prove that for rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but even cockroaches (who knows) have feelings.
However, I do not know how to prove this.
And since their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behaviour of rats rather than emotional emotions.
In any case, progress in this area is promising on the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
As with rats, I don't research language and consciousness, I don't research emotions, because I don't know if they exist.
It may seem like a shortsighted attitude to others, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly bump into a wall.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
