By the age of 35, Gebrselassie set a world record of 26 in so many areas that he won a world championship or a world record in almost every way from 1500 metres to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie missed the Olympic marathon in Beijing, which, in retrospect, may have proved to be excessive caution, that air pollution would further aggravate her asthmatic problems.
Instead, he entered the Berlin marathon.
In almost perfect conditions - at sunny time, initially at 9 °C and at the end at 13 °C - Gebrselassie won on Sunday, at an incredible speed of 2 minutes and 56 seconds per kilometer.
Since the marathon had not previously been run by runners, such as Gebrselassie, and Paul Tergat of Kenya turned to longer distances, the marathon record has decreased by more than two minutes in the last decade since the Brazilian Ronaldo da Costa won 2:06:05 in 1998 in Berlin.
