A Separate City, The Pride and Trials of Blacks
In the adventure park in Greater Orlando - a few miles away from everything that sparkles, loud and powerful - a quiet little town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience were born.
Eatonville, the first purely black city to be integrated into the country, which was the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is now not as simple as she described in 1935: "the five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, a lot of guavas and two schools without prison."
It's a pilgrimage place now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison, and Ruby Dee have been to the annual Zora Festival. The event in Eatonville is held in honor of Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet, in many ways, the city he described and made a tourist attraction, which is also included in the Florida guidebook of the Federal Writers of the Crisis Project, is separate.
Just as independent, dignified and shut-in as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that Florida city blacks often refused to share their true thoughts with white people who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing."
Even in the year when the black presidential candidate, Barack Obama, encourages an open exchange of views on the race issue, many here are distrustful of the looks of outsiders.
"We are very careful how our story is told," said 59 - year - old Hortense Jones, who lived here his whole life and is a member of the oldest church in the city.
"You have to say it correctly."
Eatonville has long been characterized by a paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historic model of black standing, but it is a community of almost 2,400 people, where poverty indicators reach double the national average.
Partly a literary node, and partly an example of a sometimes looked down, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black culture that flourishes in the shadows of oak trees.
It is not surprising, then, that the residents here are both proud and defensive.
And the picture of Eatonville has been important since Zora, (everyone here calls Hurston that).
He presented his hometown to the world in sincere, strong dialects, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and " Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guidebook have transformed the city, which lies next to Route 17, which leads from the long forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human dramas.
Hurston, who was brave in life and literature as well as drumroll, introduced his readers to the business of the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clarke, and then looked into the more intimate spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road, we find the modern public school with a brown background with white trims, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds, which Howard Miller tends, although he can barely read and write."
She mentioned the widow Dash's new husband, and she wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and whatever you might need in temporary quarters."
So in a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to autonomy, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
Clearly, the Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
Indeed, this description was not liked by everyone.
"Zora said things the way they were," said the 90 - year - old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls. Hurston made them immortal by quoting the slippery songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added: "Some people didn't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as the lively eccentric who often came home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
The 77 - year - old Augustus Franklin recalled that when Hurston stormed into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a roaring Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes, and wearing trousers in a city where people still pride themselves on their dignified dress.
Most people were charmed, Franklin said, but a lot of people did.
"People were always happy to see Zora," Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, swinging in his chair, "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor, and his books weren't published again.
Eatonville, along with most of the world, seemed to have forgotten about it.
Although he was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, he was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where he used to live.
In Eatonville, there were no significant commemorations or major public readings.
"I don't think they understand how much he's enriched the world or what he's left us," said Valerie Boyd, author of the Hurston biography published in 2003.
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-track road through the city instead of the two-track main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the community's life.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the Interstate 4 motorways connecting states on the western border of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was recovering after a difficult period in history.
Among other things, forced integration has brought an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, fighting racial mix-ups tasted hatred with the community.
"A group of white boys came over at the time and threw oranges and other things at the side of the road," Franklin said.
"There was a lady who died of it.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a letter to "The Orlando Sentinel" in 1955, Hurston questioned the decision of the Supreme Court to impose violent integration, saying that "Brown v. Board of Education" was "more a violation than a respect for my race."
Today, residents say that although the dissegregation of schools was positive in some respects, it weakened the unity of the Eatonvilleers and undermined the confidence of young people.
"Black children are used to being hugged - that's what I remember - by hugging their teacher morning and evening," N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, managing director of the nonprofit organization "Keep Eatonville Community."
"This lasted as long as the students and teachers came from a common place," he added.
"We didn't hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean, there were cultural differences between us," said Nathiri.
However, human rights have helped many other Zora Neale Hurston to rise - black writers, actors, and artists who have overcome prejudices, as she has done, with optimism and confidence, as follows: "How can anyone deprive themselves of the enjoyment of my company!
It's incomprehensible to me."
In 1975, Alice Walker went to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to restore her reputation.
Five years later, on the shelves of the bookstores, a renowned Hurston biography, written by Robert E. Hemenway, was placed on the shelves of America.
The road construction project would have started just as Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again at the center of attention.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw him as a savior.
The community started organizing a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what it would do to ruin the county's highway.
Thousands of fans arrived at the opening event two years later, and many have since returned to the celebration every January.
Several years later, the county abandoned its road construction proposal.
"Due to the five lanes of the main road, the community is revived, turned to full speed, which means real civil pride," said Nathiri.
Boyd put it simple: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the road construction project helped change the city's image of itself.
More and more people outside the city appeared, such as Lawyer Rachelle Munson, who started coming to church in 1993 and the locals began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the national historical list in 1998.
In 2006, the new one-storey library (of course named Hurston) was opened, recovered and decorated on Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remained Florida's cuckoo egg: it is not quite ten kilometers from the centre of Orlando, but sometimes it feels like it's a suburban side street during summer rain; it's as small as when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today 90% of the residents are black.)
They still take caution to the outsiders who come here looking for Eatonville's story, what he has to say.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things, such as Eatonville's oldest fresco, which a white man painted and depicts black people working in the fields, should not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, including the confident Jones teacher, who is particularly attracted to bright red, fear that their separate community is misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival grew wider, the pride of the hometown grew.
Especially young people see Eatonville more and more as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, with problems and everything, no better, no worse, no as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and confused as other racial and ethnic groups in America.
There is a genuine civic attachment from the words of Franklin's nephew Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return after graduation to take up work at the local government or the police, which he believes are in need of help.
And it seems that the younger ones have also learned to describe Eatonville correctly, such as the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
"Most people who just pass through here think this town is nothing compared to the others," said Alondra Kenon recently on Sunday after the service.
"But if someone stops and takes some time to get to know his history, it's a very nice city."
We all speak the language of finance here in New York
Nothing's changed on the surface.
If tourists didn't care about the newsstands and the huge television screens on Times Square, they wouldn't notice they were in the middle of a storm.
They would never realize that with the glass-walled, beehive-shaped offices above their heads, bankers and venture capital managers who have held New York in their power have been living the hardest days since 1929.
The couriers are still rolling their metal tea trucks through the sidewalks, carrying cupcakes filled with muffin for morning meetings.
Men with Spanish lips are still squirming between the blocks, carrying as human mule fifty ironed shirts hanging from a yoke-like noose on their shoulders.
Office workers are still lining up for their breakfast sweet pastries at the food trucks on the sidewalk, and it is still impossible to catch a taxi on weekdays between 4:00 and 7:00 p.m.
I didn't feel there was any crisis until Thursday afternoon, despite all the ominous news, I decided to open a new bank account.
Though I purposely planned to take care of it during the afternoon's rest in the local account of my JP Morgan Chase bank, there were about 20 people standing in front of me.
Not at the window of the bank teller, where you can withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service counter, where older customers order a checkbook, tourists ask for directions to the Macy's store, and where new customers open bank accounts.
Many of them, I learned later from Starr, the banker who had been assigned to me, had the same intention as I did.
Unlike me, however, they have already taken their money from smaller banks in their home, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
Money was taken from the so-called savings banks (such as housing cooperatives), credit cooperatives and small-town savings banks that operate only in one state and are supposed to treat their clients as family members.
In the last year, 15 of these banks have been silently destroyed.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with a capital of $327 billion, went bankrupt, and when the New Yorkers left for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, was looking for a bank saver with $440 billion in savings.
The office and shop workers in front of me, fear of another collapse, moved their money to a bank that seemed like a safe haven, the bank that buys most capital injections on Wall Street.
In the last few weeks, the ordinary people of New York have become experts in finance.
A woman at the local Chinese department store on her phone talked about the bankrupt Lehman Brothers bank and his huge-looking CEO, Dick Fuld, as if he were complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the janitor in uniform on the block of my apartment, in his 50s, changed the subject, and we weren't talking about Brad and Angelina or my grocery delivery like we used to.
He spoke to me after I went to the bank: "I invested all my savings in money market instruments.
I've changed, I'm not taking any chances."
