"I don't take pictures on stage because I'd like to introduce the artist from a personal point of view"
No sets, no ruffles, no dancing shoes.
The masterpieces of flamenco from close to the body, without the excitement of the performance: to get to know the everyday face of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, ordinary people.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in the intimate, distant moments from the audience, when we can look at a personal movement, grab the depth of an eye caught, or marvel at the inaction of the artist who is about to perform on stage.
In the German photo series Günther Bauer Flamenco-people, he combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarist with this less-known everyday side of the masters.
Through the photos, the special iconography of flamenco is presented from different angles.
The exhibition, which is part of Flamenco's Month of Photography, "represents the growing international significance of flamenco from day to day," says the creator, adding that Flamenco-people "can be a character for anyone, since, in view of the images, the observer realizes that these images do not represent artists in a typical way.
These people on the street are artists who are capable of bringing passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and captivating the audience.
At the same time, stage photography is not suitable for grabbing their personality.
Their personality and character are in the deepest part of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the greats of flamenco with the help of the camera."
The Cante de las Minas festival gave a kick-start start to Bauer's long journey in 1997, during which he made portraits of flamenco singers, guitarist and dancer with a record camera.
These portraits quote classical photography thanks to the camera and the theme selection.
However, the use of various stylistic tools breaks with traditional visual representation and suggests modernity. The following idea faithfully reflects Bauer's idea of flamenco: "This is a music with traditional roots, which, however, changes day by day and is always fascinating."
Not dancing, not singing or music in itself, but rather the artist's personality and character charm the audience.
In the days, the main motif of the works that can be seen in the El Fotomata gallery is the search for the essentials, the encounter with the artistic wharf, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and visualization.
The known figures of flamenco, including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, represent this photo collection of nearly 60 artists.
The project also became a flamenco anthology, about which an album covering the portraits presented at the exhibition will soon be released.
Two years ago, Bauer's passion for portraits prompted him to repeat the idea with the series "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportART Project").
Although the concept of Flamenco-people is slightly different, the photographer adds: "I really like to photograph people, get to know them and enter their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre in photography is portrait.
People you meet, people you meet, people you don't even know sometimes, people that just take a few minutes to shoot.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.
The exhibition from the portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled Flamenco-people, can be seen in the El Fotomata Gallery, which is parallel to Alameda de Hércules, until October 16.
