Those who speak in their sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up and tell them what happened to them that day, but those who talk in their sleep.
The phenomenon may seem scary at first, but it's actually quite harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquismus.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure some of you have been told that you spoke at night.
Regarding its frequency, it can be completely rapsodic (for example, it only occurs once in a high fever disease) or more systematic (every day, once a week or monthly) and usually the child does not remember anything the next day.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single underlying cause.
Often accompanied by other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night alarms, bed-wetting (enuresis nocturna) or sleepwalking, but this is not legal either.
As has already been mentioned, it can be accompanied by a high fever or stress or heightened excitement.
In any case, they've been little studied so far.
The intensity of speech also varies greatly.
It may be quiet, calm, out of incoherent words, murmuring, but in contrast, it may also occur in the form of shouting, crying, or longer speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is advisable to observe the child and contact a specialist. The study may reveal whether there is a problem that causes great anxiety and thus offers a solution.
As mentioned above, this is a benign phenomenon, and therefore there is no cure unless it is associated with other manageable forms of sleep disorder (e.g. insomnia or stress).
However, there are a few things we can do, and here is a bunch of preventive measures:
Make sure that the child remains calm before going to bed.
Choose comforting games and avoid children watching fear - inspiring or more aggressive TV shows or shows.
Children who tend to get nervous or have difficulty relaxing are taught some relaxation methods to help them find inner peace.
This will help the child to sleep better.
If you do start talking while you're sleeping, let's try to stay calm.
Remember, it's harmless to the child, and the next day, they won't remember anything.
Useful advice
Don't wake the child.
It would be pointless, because the child is unconscious, but he'd be out of sleep.
Even though he talks, he actually sleeps longer and rests.
Remember, if you have frequent episodes of severe anxiety, it is advisable to contact a specialist or explore what triggers extreme anxiety in the child.
If you speak clearly (this is the rarest case), don't start asking questions to find out anything from him.
It would be unnecessary, since he is not conscious enough to collect his thoughts during sleep.
On the other hand, you can only hear the speech, but you can't see the dream images associated with it, so be careful of the interpretation of what you hear and any conclusions.
Never tell the kid they can question him at night about his secrets.
Not even as a joke.
This causes a great deal of anxiety.
So the most important thing is not to worry, because it's just a few minutes of harmless episode.
