Blood Safe Again
Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its founding yesterday. President Dr. Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, because Héma-Quebec has now become one of the safest and most effective blood donor companies in the world.
Most importantly, he managed to regain people's trust, which was seriously shaken by the scandal about infected blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross blood supply service was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general uproar, in February 1994, the government of Canada, led by Judge Horace Krever, launched a formal investigation to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make proposals to avoid similar future cases.
While Judge Krever has submitted a delayed report, some provinces have set up their own committee to design a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gelineau Committee fulfilled this task.
Following the Gelineau and Krever reports, two blood supply services were established in Canada: one is Hema-Québec serving Quebec, and the other is all the other provinces and the Canadian Blood Supply Corporation responsible for two territories.
"When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in Quebec's blood supply system," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the following years, however, we have regained people's trust as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field." Décary proudly states that nearly 94% of the population in Quebec considered Héma-Québec reliable at the beginning of 2008.
However, Dr Décary does not forget that "trust is extremely fragile."
Since the foundation of Héma-Québec on 28 September 1998, it has applied the principle of caution.
During this period, a number of cases of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, have been discovered in Europe, says the doctor, who has been managing the company since its founding in 1998.
"We had no idea if this disease was spreading through blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations in the Krever and Gelineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and are at risk of developing a serious disease, we must apply exclusion measures. In this case, we were talking about Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which causes the brain to change, thus inevitably leading to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who have spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was established beyond any doubt that the disease was transmitted by blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the principle of caution."
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that allows the HIV virus to be more susceptible to diagnosis. It is a nuclear acid test (NAT) that can directly detect the virus in the blood of blood donors rather than antibodies against the virus on which the tests used previously were built.
The NAT test allowed us to shorten the window period, which is afraid of infection until we can detect the virus in the blood using our technical tools, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
Thus, they significantly reduced the risk that blood donors would unknowingly infect blood and that this could not be detected.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of the spread of AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of receiving HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
"In other words, this means we should distribute 12 million blood products while someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes 400 to 500 000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and for someone to become infected with HIV through a blood product.
I think that today anyone can accept or prescribe blood transfusions to restore health, says the number one leader of Héma-Québec.
"The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogen is going into the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, gets into the blood with insect bites.
Therefore, we must be on guard at all times," said Dr. Décary, then stressing that apart from emergency reserves, Héma-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
"Aging the population also increases demand.
Since anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need replacement of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the population of blood donors, as the number of people in the network who are willing to donate blood accounts for only 3% of the population in Quebec.
However, all healthy individuals aged at least 18 years who meet the eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have been in a country where malaria is devastating are not entitled to donate blood for a year.
"With this 3 percent, we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare to run out of supplies.
However, we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that existing ones are getting older, because they can no longer give blood after a while.
However, it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, but it is even harder to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In today's rushing world, a man has barely an hour to go and give blood," Francine Décary regrets.
Héma-Québec, which holds an annual budget of USD 297 million, provides not only blood products but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin tissue, which are used almost exclusively for severely burned individuals.
These tissues are analyzed, converted and frozen and then placed at Hema-Quebec, which also manages a single public stem cell bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, once treated as medical waste, can produce blood that is rich in stem cells, thus allowing the treatment of severe diseases (such as leukaemia).
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the entry into our bank of the thousandth cord blood sample, and we plan to take more than a thousand new samples each year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering them to transplants," said Dr. Décary, who said that the umbilical cord blood collection program is very popular today.
"Many mothers are sad because they do not have the opportunity to do so" - it is true, because Héma-Québec cannot make this complex and costly program available in all of Quebec's hospitals.
