The psychology of over-bidding: why are we giving out more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overestimate goods.
The neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior have been revealed by researchers at the New York University of Neurologists and economists.
According to their study published in Science magazine, people do not want to fall behind in a race such as eBay's auction, so they pay too high a price.
The research was trying to map this neurological pattern of play using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other took part in a playful auction, while the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method was used to examine the active brain areas of the test subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction game - in which the over-bidding of the other party is an essential element - the striatum under-cortex complex was activated intensively when the game was lost.
In addition to several other functions, this brain area plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the rise in the price can be explained by avoiding the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theory, the members of the economist of the research group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this, three groups bid against one partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was and they placed their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they came out of the game winning, they would be rewarded with another $15 worth of money.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 just before the auction, but the members of the group lost this money in the event of a losing auction.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, only that they emphasized the win for one of them and the loss for the other.
However, by proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team who played against "loss" were willing to bets higher than the control and "winner" groups.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
To date, they only explained the events at the auction with the joy of victory and risk avoidance.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories by giving us a third explanation now," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
There are hundreds of thousands of people infected with hepatitis at home, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients are often unaware that they are infected.
Hepatitis is a generic name for infectious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
Their symptoms have many similarities, characteristic of hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are different.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the gastrointestinal tract (e.g. contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (dondo, vaginal secretion, saliva).
In any case, travelers should be vaccinated against A and B viruses, and there is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after eating the infected food, accompanied by generally feeling unwell, weakness, abdominal discomfort, nausea.
After this, jaundice occurs on the skin and whites of the eyes, stools are clear, urine becomes dark, healing may take two to three weeks.
A million people worldwide die of the more serious disease, liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected patients will receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can also lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected do not even know about the disease, because the pathogen insidiously kills the liver's cells, in many cases the first symptoms occur in 20-30 years.
Thus, early prevention and regular screening tests are very important.
In three groups, this disease is much more than average: between people who had had had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
The number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C in the world is currently estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease may already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is worth contacting the general physician if any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
Recognizing the disease in time can be cured, the virus can be eradicated from the body, thus eliminating infectiveness and preventing cancer.
30 September is the World Day for Hepatitis, which was held for the first time in 2004 by organisations representing patients around the world.
It aims to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, its causes and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God hurt less?
According to a recent study, religious faith acts as a kind of painkiller, which could have made the death of Catholic martyrs easier.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how belief in God affects people's sense of pain, reported British Telegraph.
In the framework of the rather bizarre study, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were electroshocked, while they all studied a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the pain.
Thanks to the technique that scans the human brain, it was also revealed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that was responsible for controlling pain.
The study is the first in a series of research that involves scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university, in addition to academics.
The investigation was carried out precisely by attaching a sparkly device to the left hand of the test subject, which provided electroshock.
Researchers asked the participants to take a strong look at two paintings, the picture of the Virgin Mary and Leonardo da Vinci, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, with hermeline painted in the 15th century.
The investigators hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would create a religious state among believers, while the da Vinci picture was chosen because it was not too different from the other and thought it to be soothing.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner machine, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive episodes while either looking at the religious theme or the general picture.
The Catholics reported that when they saw the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe" like they were "careful" and "relaxed, filled with peace."
While looking at the religious picture, 12 percent less pain was reported than when Leonardo's work was seen before you.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself participated in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, including atheists, only the right photo should be found.
"We should find a picture that they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should and in many cases will change our personality," added Wright.
After the great results, the question is, if Leonardo or a similar-caliber painter showed a picture of a madonna to the believers, how would that affect their pain control?
Would the sight of the quality Virgin Mary bring even better results?
