The flight of the bumblebee is imitated by the intelligent car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collision if not to mimic obstacles in the natural world?
Bees, for example.
In the surprising project presented at CATEC in Japan, the bee has given Nissan engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C bio-implanted car robot control system, a robotic minicar that has been provided with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate aim of facilitating the development of a system that eliminates all collisions.
During flight, every bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is in fact very similar to our safety shield, explained Kazuhiro Doi, technological PR and R &amp; D brand director at the exhibition.
Its role is important for the complex eye of the uterus, which can see in all directions at more than 300 degrees of vision.
To copy the complex eye function, the engineers reached out to the idea of a laser telemeter.
This identifies obstacles within a 2 m range of 180 degrees before BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into an action to avoid collision.
Within a fraction of the second, the obstacle is detected, and then the car robot, imitating the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by turning its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid collision.
In any way other than the current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
"If that were not the case, the car robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Andoh Toshiyuki, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology is the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety shield, a layer within which the collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
However, in a way other than bees, the deviation should not be directed upwards, downward or diagonally, only two-dimensional and only towards the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibility for bees to avoid other bees, they used only rotating motion and acceleration and slowing down as an option available to the car robot.
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means that they have a longer life span than lithium ion.
According to Andoh, an intuitive intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process data, even less to store it.
This device will only have to process and react to a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory continuously.
There's no need for gigabyte or megabyte-sized memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate avoidance technology, which, according to Nissan's estimation, could enter mass-produced cars within ten years.
The assembly of the unit with the GPS-satellite navigation system may provide additional application to guide the driver to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
