The written version of the $700 billion economic rescue package law for the purchase of banks' bad loans in several instalments has been completed.
In the first round, half of the money is spent.
During the further talks that took place after midnight on Saturday, Eastern Coast Time, congressional leaders came to an agreement in the day - long debate around a total of $700 billion rescue package, reports Reuters.
"We have made great progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic President of the American House of Representatives, who said that all that remains is to be written.
The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Minister of Finance Henry Paulson stated that the programme will work and be effective, but there is also a need for further work. Pelosi said that this is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the cycle of the economy around.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets in Washington on Sunday evening (i.e. Monday morning at two o'clock in Central European Time), but did not cause a spectacular rise in the skins.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote on the draft of the Act on the programme, which is called the Economic Emergency Stabilization Act of 2008, and then it will be the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and the White House also welcomed the news of the settlement.
We are pleased with the progress made last night and appreciate the efforts of the two parties to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy, said Tony Fratto, spokesperson of the White House.
Otherwise, the programme differs from the original proposal of the Bush Administration, which would have meant that the $700 billion would have been spent on the purchase of low-quality debt securities.
Now, for the first time, up to half of the 700 billion will be spent using 250 billion immediately after Congress is expected to vote on the matter on Monday, from which the Ministry of Finance buys low-grade securities with credit background, and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
The program will be monitored by a separate body, which will be attended by the president of the Federal Reserve.
The spending of the other half of 700 billion depends on another decision of Congress.
Under the law, the Ministry of Finance can use combined tactics: it can buy bad loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities at the same time and other types of "toxic" loans.
The purchase can take place in the framework of auctions and directly - the Ministry's authorities have stated.
The legislation allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance scheme, where the financial portfolio guarantees the means of concern for which companies will pay a fee corresponding to the expected damage.
Henry Paulson said that the law provides the necessary means to meet the urgent needs of the US financial system of up to $700 billion, whether it is about the widespread purchase of bad assets, whether it is about their insurance or the collapse of a large financial institution.
We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed, he added.
However, heads of banks in distress and awaiting state aid can expect the government to limit their exit money, which the overseas slang simply calls a golden parachute.
Payments are limited only in certain cases, and the limits depend on the way the Ministry of Finance provides assistance.
In essence, the restriction means that if the Ministry buys an auction, an extra tax is levied on the golden parachute, unless the senior bank leader is retired.
When buying bad loans directly, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that management money is not excessive.
The picture includes that existing gold parachute contracts do not change, the restriction applies only to new ones to encourage participation in the program.
This is the first time in American history that there will be legal restrictions on the remuneration of CEOs - commented the President of the House's Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank of the Democratic Party.
In addition, in the banks participating in the programme, the State acquires the right to acquire, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as they can eventually win the transaction once the economy and the rescued bank recovers.
The draft law states that, over the next five years, the President will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to return the expected losses to taxpayers from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were some who expressed doubts about the plan.
This is not what the American citizens have asked us to do, i.e. not protect taxpayers' dollars, said the Republican representative Darrell Issa of California.
His Democratic colleague in Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believed that the actions were being promoted by the same people responsible for Wall Street's collapse.
