The domestic sales prices of industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, reports KSH.
The prices of industrial export sales were 1.1 per cent higher than in July 2008, with a decrease of 3.9 per cent compared to one year earlier.
As a result of domestic and export price changes, industrial producer prices were 0.7 per cent higher than the previous month and 3.2 per cent higher than the previous year.
The domestic sales prices of the industry increased only minimally by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in manufacturing sectors also increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The highest increase in prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather product and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), mainly due to the 4,6 percent increase in the production of bags, straps and a 2.5 percent monthly increase in footwear production.
The higher price levels of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 percent).
Price reductions occurred in the oil processing (1.4 percent), electrical machinery, instrument production (0.9 percent) and wood processing (0.1 percent) sectors, to a minimum.
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
In other manufacturing sectors, we measured price increases of between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In August prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, which represents a significant weight in domestic sales of industry, increased by 0.3 percent, mainly due to the prolonged impact of the official gas price increase from 1 July.
In 12 months' comparison, prices in the oil processing sector increased to the highest extent (32.4 percent) in terms of domestic sales of manufacturing sectors.
In the fabricated products sector, there was an 11 percent increase in food, drink and tobacco production, representing a significant weight, of 13.2 percent.
Price reductions occurred in the textiles, textile products (2.5 percent) and electric machinery and instruments (0.3 percent) sectors.
In other manufacturing sectors, the rate of increase was between 0.6 per cent and 9.1 per cent.
Prices have increased by 10.2 percent over the last year in the manufacturing industry as a whole.
The prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector exceeded 18.7 percent a year earlier.
Domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase in the capital goods manufacturing sectors (0.7 percent) in August, among the sectors for which they are intended.
In consumer goods manufacturing sectors, prices have increased by 0.3 percent and prices in energy and downstream sectors have not changed compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, the highest price increase compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in energy and downstream sectors (18.6 percent).
In the consumer goods manufacturing sectors, we measured an increase in prices of 6.8 per cent and a decrease in prices of 1.4 per cent for capital goods.
The export sales prices of the industry in HUF increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month and decreased by 3.9 percent in 12 months comparison.
