The sooner the Roma student starts school, the more opportunities she has to become a productive member of the labour market; they contribute to the national budget through taxes on income and consumption.
"Romas should be guaranteed the right to quality education and the elimination of their low quality and separate education in the right of EU citizenship," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the Member, the aim and action-oriented cooperation of the European Union is necessary to speed up the dissegregation processes in schools immediately, and it is essential to ensure that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives are properly enforced.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, Roma children must be given the opportunities of democratic space to contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens," said Járóka.
