MP3 players can cause hearing damage
Longer and high volume listening to portable players such as MP3 devices can cause permanent hearing loss
published in Brussels on the basis of the opinion published today by the European Commission, the new and newly identified Scientific Committee on Health Risks (SCENIHR).
"The opinion shows that 5-10 percent of those who listen to their portable music player for more than one hour per day for five years can suffer permanent hearing loss," says the explanation.
"It is worrying that young people who mass and often use high volume portable music players and mobile phones are unaware that they can irreversibly damage their hearing," said Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific surveys indicate an indisputable risk that we urgently need to respond to," the EU Commissioner added.
The most important task is to inform consumers and disseminate information on this.
In the light of this opinion, we also need to review existing control systems so that they can work properly and keep pace with the latest technologies."
Brussels invited the independent scientific committee to examine the problem in view of the prevalence of portable music players and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise.
"The researchers confirm that we have cause for concern, and the European Commission, in cooperation with Member States and stakeholders, is ready to examine possible measures for the protection of children and minors exposed to noise from portable players and similar devices," he concluded.
