Elite in Danger
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House did not vote in favour of the $700 billion rescue package presented by the White House: most Americans were more interested and still interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is supported by the New York Times yesterday, which informs us that the current crisis has led to a break in the Republican Party, which is showing an increasing division between the traditional, restrained Eastern coastal attitude to support federal institutions and business circles and the new anti- Washington and financial direction that is growing in the Central and Southern states.
This line was expressed critically in the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
However, this event is just one of the major changes that the economic restructuring that is still taking place allows us to anticipate or see, not only in the United States, but in the whole Western world, and perhaps even outside.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, is only accelerating the long-standing phenomena that have been solidified in this new atmosphere and are finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is re-activation, bringing the dual category of state sovereignty back to the public in relation to a kind of re-nationalisation of the economy.
The crisis affects banking and financial institutions which, while having a close relationship with the rest of the world, are primarily and fairly widespread, bringing with them people and families living in one country, one state.
This, in turn, is a direct political problem for those on the government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also voters.
Thus, the crisis seems to be global in economic terms, but in political terms it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be largely out of line: the European Union is an eloquent proof of this, which cannot establish a uniform political direction between different interests and different national strategies.
Thus, everyone expects the intervention, the rescue package, the recovery and the new rules, but especially the opening up of funds: because, in a difficult situation, only the individual states have economic resources, a financial stock that may be able to make things right.
They have both the means and the power to use them: they have two invaluable resources, which no other market and no international organisation will possibly have at any time to such an extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on nation state is fully in line with the fact that recent economic growth attaches increasing importance to a factor that is closely linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the network, we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we suddenly had to realize that our future was increasingly dependent on things that were, in the least, abstract, such as water, crops and oil.
From things that can be transported from one side of the planet to another, they are wholly linked to a confined location, an area.
So whoever controls the area has a lot more cards than the one who, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
I'd like to move on to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of fault line.
Who says territory, state, government, necessarily says politics, in other words leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to produce two interrelated phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition of the need for credible leadership is someone who can handle the events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially economic leaders, has brought about a total loss of credit, who have proved completely inadequate and demonstrated that many areas are still blurry.
Together, the two are even more important and, in a sense, more disturbing: a sense of lack of credit, intolerance, inadequacy and separation, which affects the entire leadership elite in more and more Western countries.
So it seems that the belief in the wider population is that the social elite's time until now is over. It has expired before they have made their actions, their experiences, their way of life, their culture, their own in the complex sense of the word. This makes the social elite increasingly alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In short, the demand for leadership, in a covert form, feeds a wide-ranging but strong delegation movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This is reflected in the unexpected "insurrections" of voters, or in the sudden changes in the public mood in recent times. For example, the rise of conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Union in Britain, or the rebellion of American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the Italian right).
It seems that the traditional elite, together with its parties, programs, and even its customs, press and prestigious intellectuals, are becoming less and less aware of what has been happening for some time in the deeper layers of Western society. Furthermore, the economic crisis is growing, spreading, and is potentially capable of causing ever-increasing anger.
Nevertheless, talking about "the imminent rebellion of the masses" would, frankly, be exaggeration.
But keeping an open mind is not bad at all.
