No juice!
Care should be taken with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These high-vitamin-containing, mainly popular in the summer, thirsting drinks, if they are added together with certain life-saving medicines, alter their absorption by increasing or reducing their effect, as the case may be. This may have serious health consequences.
David Bailey, Professor of the University of Western Ontario of London, pointed out the risks of the combination of canned or fresh fruit juices and certain medicinal products. The professor announced at 236 national meetings of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia: a glass of grapefruit, orange or apple juice can reduce the absorption of certain life-saving medicines, thereby preventing their beneficial effects and endangering the health of the patient.
Grapefruit juice was already on the defendant's bench when it was found that it was able to increase the effects of some antibiotics, antihistamines, anti-anxiety, pacemakers, and neuromedicines to levels that could be considered toxic.
RISK MEDICINAL PRODUCTS - Two years ago, the Italian Pharmaceutical Institute itself published the news in its official bulletin and warned doctors and patients to take seriously the risks associated with such co-administration and to pay attention to what they drink when taking medicines such as Diazepam or methadone.
GRAPEFRUIT IS NOT the only one - According to researchers, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that inhibit the effectiveness of medicines.
A long list of active substances whose absorption is hindered by grapefruit and other fruit juices could be listed.
Michele Carruba, professor of pharmaceuticals at the University of Milan, draws attention to this: "Such discoveries are usually immediately signalled to the various national and international pharmaceutical institutions, who, if necessary, will ensure that they change the information contained in the product.
