Good-bye, old Cinema Paradiso, the time of the old movie halls in the cities is over.
Traditional movies close in favor of the Multiplexes.
"A city where there are no movies, a blind city, is like a face without eyes."
The pictures taken by director Giuseppe Tornatore are an effective demonstration of what is happening in Italian cities, but also in rural regions.
The displacement of cinemas - the appearance of large, multi-room cinemas in the suburbs, and as a result the demise of single-room cinemas in city centres - seems inevitable and irreversible, but at the same time bears all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
When historical and memory-filled places disappear, "it's like a friend leaving, a friend with whom we shared our journey and many experiences," says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which, twenty years ago, represented an Oscar Award and the Grand Prix of the Cannes Festival to Tornatore, tells the lyrical story of a small-town cinema, the yearning, after a movie experience that may have been lost forever.
The largest association of operators, Anec's data, is clear: 316 traditional cinemas have closed in the last five years. The biggest losses were recorded by cinemas in large cities: 10 cinemas closed in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin, and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions, Emilia-Romagna, which lost 82 single-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardia (41).
And that the rise in the number of multiplexes is the only proof of their disappearance, since Italy has the highest number of newly opened multi-room cinemas in these three regions: in the last five years, the number of rooms has increased by 195 in Lombardia, 81 in Tuscany and the same in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally," says the president of Anec Paolo Protti. "It is okay to build new facilities, but it should also ensure the survival of existing ones, because when a city cinema closes, not all visitors are willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention uncharged financial funds intended to support operators: the state's overdue debt is estimated at about EUR 10 million.
From an ethical and moral point of view, it is shameful that the government does not comply with the legislation in force.
To maintain the market, 16-18 million euros a year would be needed."
This is the first Italian city that has decided, in its concern over the closures, to remedy the problem in order to protect and boost single-room cinemas in the suburbs and downtown, through an agreement between the municipality and Anec.
The provisions would include tax incentives to operators and benefits to the public to facilitate accessibility: viewers can drive into restricted zones and park in certain parking lots with reduced rates.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example, even by introducing other measures.
However, it is also certain that traditional cinemas, in order to be able to combat multiplex control, need to improve sound and image quality, because today's audience is more demanding.
Protecting traditional cinema has always been an important question for me: the closure of Supercinema in Bagheria, where I spent my childhood and youth, gave me the spark that ultimately made me do Cinema Paradiso, although I've been thinking about it for 10 years.
I've lived in Rome for 25 years, so when I go to the via Nazionale in front of the closed Rialto or Quirinale in order not to see the black posters of dust, I turn my head. I've had so many experiences here."
