An inexhaustible energy source that accounts for 70 percent of the planet's surface and which is just being discovered by large international energy companies
Waves, ocean currents, tides, all renewable energy sources that have been eyeballed by giants like Chevron who are now trying to get their hands on it.
They've been searching for a hundred years for the possibility of getting energy from the sea's movements, and in the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research has increased.
Around 1980, when the price of oil fell, the idea of using marine energy was set aside, but today the demand for environmental protection and the rise in oil prices give the sector a new impetus.
The London World Energy Council (WEC) estimates in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be covered by offshore wave facilities.
This is twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
The giants are on the move.
Enersis was the first company to commit to marine energy and in 2005 signed an agreement on a power plant to be established in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary step when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed, and more and more companies are voting for marine energy, including those who have so far been committed to supporting traditional energy.
"Chevron studies technologies that harness the energy of the oceans and considers the possibility of cooperation with us," said a spokesperson for an associated US oil giant, the Wall Street Journal economic newspaper.
The cooperation in question concerns the acquisition of a permit from the US Energy Commission to launch a offshore energy project in Alaska.
The issue is not small, especially considering that the US is currently in Alaska, and President Bush has also recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey Ocean Power are also on their way out of the sea.
The technology is waiting to be developed.
According to experts, we are still talking about primitive technology, even because energy from the sea does not dissipate doubts about the environmental impact.
The existing facilities, similar to those of Portugal or Scotland, are all small and therefore do not cause too much problems with the ecosystem.
However, in order to generate energy on a larger scale, it is necessary to have installations with a higher environmental impact.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a interconnected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves and moving up and down the buoys are converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure is turning a turbine that feeds a generator.
The electricity goes to the mainland on cables under the sea.
For now, there are four similar facilities in the planning phase that are just waiting for the federal permit, and some of the energy generated would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started power generation for a shopping mall and a parking lot with the help of six submarine turbines in the East River Strait of New York.
At tides, the movement of water turns the blades of the turbines, and this rotation feeds the generator.
Verdant stated that it has a long list of partners who are only waiting for permission to use energy.
The tides after the waves.
At present, the opportunities that can be exploited through tides deserve special attention.
Although it is a temporary phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and therefore can be considered as a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as the other coastal states, spent $7.5 million in 2008 to exploit the energy provided by the tide, which is expected to increase to 35 million in 2009.
